{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure is at a module handoff boundary (request builder -> API client). A unit test of only a helper function can miss dropped/overwritten labels during wiring/serialization. Real OS/network is not required: behavior text is about request contents, so an in-process fake transport can catch it. Rejected higher level: no behavior text requires live HTTP or model judgment.","test_description":"Wire the classifier module with a fake API client that captures outbound payloads. Invoke classification with a known taxonomy and assert every valid label is present in the actual dispatched request payload.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure can occur in response parsing + normalization handoff, not just pure mapping logic. A module-level test with a stubbed provider response catches whether the unexpected label leaks through the public API. Rejected higher levels: behavior text only needs handling of a returned value; no real OS/network or model-quality dependency is required.","test_description":"Use a stub API client that returns an out-of-taxonomy label (e.g., \"medical\"). Call the module’s classify entrypoint and assert returned value is exactly \"unknown\".","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.4,"Integration":0.56,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This behavior explicitly targets one local normalization step and deterministic mapping from identical input to identical output. No cross-module boundary or I/O is required to expose the failure.","test_description":"Call the normalization function repeatedly with the same raw response fixture and taxonomy, asserting identical final label each time.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior text requires repeated live AI calls and depends on real provider outputs; mocks hide non-deterministic model behavior. This is a single agentic decision boundary (one model call per classification), not a multi-step agent pipeline. Rejected Workflow: no sequential multi-agent/model stages are specified.","test_description":"Run multiple real classification calls for the same document/taxonomy, recording raw provider response and final label each run. Assert label changes only on runs where provider response content changed; if raw response is unchanged, final label must remain unchanged.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.25,"Agentic":0.7,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The bug appears at construction-to-dispatch handoff: over-budget payload might still be sent even if local token logic exists. Integration with a fake client verifies enforcement before send. Rejected System/Agentic: behavior text says enforcement happens before dispatch, so no real network or model output is required.","test_description":"Configure a small token budget and input that exceeds it. Invoke classify with a fake API client and assert policy outcome (truncate or reject) occurs and no over-budget request is dispatched.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.45,"Integration":0.5,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This explicitly depends on live provider-reported usage from an external AI API call; stubs can mask real tokenization/accounting differences. Per LLM-dependency rule, tests passing through real AI API should default to Agentic unless purely transport plumbing, which this is not.","test_description":"Execute real classification calls on representative documents and capture provider-reported token usage from responses. Assert reported usage is <= configured budget for each call.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.27,"Agentic":0.7,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure is in retry orchestration across modules (error handling, backoff, re-dispatch). A stubbed client can deterministically return rate-limit then success to reveal failures; real OS/network is not required. Rejected higher levels: behavior concerns control flow on provider status, not model output quality or multi-step agent pipeline.","test_description":"Use a fake API client scripted to return rate-limit on first call and success on second. Verify classifier waits/backs off per policy, retries, and returns success to caller instead of surfacing the initial rate-limit error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}}]}
